Which of the following represents the electron configuration of the transition metal Mo?

explanation.concept_text: Electron configuration is the distribution of electrons of an atom or molecule in atomic or molecular orbitals. The first three orbitals are the s, p and d orbitals which hold 2, 6, and 10 electrons respectively. When we try to solve this question, at first glance the electron configuration of molybdenum appears to be: 1s 2 2s 2 2p 6 3s 2 3p 6 4s 2 3d 10 4p 6 5s 2 4d 4 or [Kr] 5s 2 4d 4 However, there are certain elements that have special exceptions, molybdenum being one of them since it is a transition metal . Transition metals such as molybdenum need an electron to fill their d- orbitals because it is energetically favourable to have a half full d- orbital; they get this electron from the full s- orbital. This occurs because elements with either half or full sub-orbitals are more stable than if they were empty orbitals. Therefore, we take the original electron configuration of [Kr] 5s 2 4d 4 , and we remove one electron from the 5 s and add it to the 4d- orbital, to get: 1s 2 2s 2 2p 6 3s 2 3p 6 4s 2 3d 10 4p 6 5s 1 4d 5 or [Kr] 5s 1 4d 5 This effectively results in a partial occupancy of the s- orbital and a full d- orbital. The same rule can be applied to the 4th group which are the transition metals with 4 electrons in their d- orbitals. The image shown below provides a visualization of the four blocks on the periodic table: CC BY 4.0

question.text: Each of the following describes a procedure used when measuring chemical compounds EXCEPT one. Which one is the EXCEPTION?

options.label: D.
options.text: Place the sample in a container before measuring

explanation.concept_text: To determine the answer to this question, we must understand different laboratory safety. One of which is that chemicals need to be measured accurately, otherwise, they may be too weak or too strong and can become a safety hazard. When measuring solids like powders and granules, you should use a scoop or measuring spoon to place the substance in to a small container that has already been weighed on the scale beforehand. When measuring liquids on a scale, always measure the substance on a flat surface and make sure to slowly pour the substance into a cup, glass or cylinder tube until you have the correct weight. In either case, it is very important that you do not place/pour the chemical directly on to the scale without any containers since you could get an inaccurate reading and is also a safety hazard. Based on this, the answer would be Option A. measure directly on the scale .
explanation.poe_text: Option B . Tare the scale each time – This option is incorrect because this will take into account the weight of the tray, which is an important step to perform before adding weight. Option C. Use sterile instruments – This option is incorrect because it is very important to use sterile instruments to prevent contamination. Option D . Place the sample in a container before measuring – This option is incorrect because in addition to being safe, this will prevent spilling and increase accuracy. Option E . Wear personal protective equipment – This option is incorrect because this should always be done when handling chemical compounds.

question.text: Which of the following molecules has a dipole moment?

explanation.concept_text: We can quickly identify HF as a polar molecule because it consists of two different atoms with a large difference in electronegativity. Thus, the correct answer is Option B . For other molecules, we can examine the structure as follows.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. CO 2 – This option is incorrect because CO 2 has a linear structure. Each oxygen is double bonded to the carbon which does not have any lone pairs so the resulting structure is linear. Option C. Cl 2 – This option is incorrect because the bond between two identical atoms must necessarily be nonpolar since neither will have greater electronegativity than the other. Option D. BH 3 – This option is incorrect because boron is unique in its ability to be stable with only 3 covalent bonds and no lone pairs. Thus, borane has a trigonal planar structure and is nonpolar. Note that while borane can exist on its own, it still some tendency to react with itself to form diborane, B 2 H 6 , which achieves an octet around boron. Option E. CCl 4 – This option is incorrect because carbon can form four covalent bonds at most and each of those bonds in carbon tetrachloride is with chlorine. Thus, carbon tetrachloride will display symmetry and so does not have a net dipole moment.

Which of the following best describes the second law of thermodynamics?

options.label: A.
options.text: The entropy of the system plus the surroundings remains constant or decreases over time

options.label: B.
options.text: For a spontaneous process, the entropy of the universe increases

options.label: C.
options.text: For a spontaneous process, the entropy of the system increases

options.label: D.
options.text: Energy cannot be created nor destroyed

options.label: E.
options.text: For a spontaneous process, the entropy of the surroundings decreases

correct_answer_text: For a spontaneous process, the entropy of the universe increases

explanation.concept_text: The second law of thermodynamics relates to entropy , which is the degree of disorder, or randomness, in the system. The law states that for any spontaneous process, the entropy of the universe (system + surroundings) or an isolated system must increase. Entropy may remain constant during a reversible process or during equilibrium, but it can never decrease. There are 3 types of thermodynamic systems, which can be visualized in the image below: CC BY 4.0 Canadian DAT Pro Tip: The second law applies to the universe, so for a system that is not isolated, entropy may increase or decrease or remain constant. It is the entropy of the system PLUS the entropy of the surroundings which must increase or otherwise remain constant for a reversible process.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. The entropy of the system plus the surroundings remains constant or decreases over time - This option is incorrect because the system plus the surroundings refers to the universe, and the second law states that the entropy of the universe increases. Option C. For a spontaneous process, the entropy of the system increases - This option is incorrect because it is the entropy of the universe that necessarily increases. The universe consists of the system and surroundings which may or may not display increases in entropy respectively. Option D. Energy cannot be created nor destroyed - Although the statement is correct, this option is incorrect as it refers to the first law of thermodynamics. Option E. For a spontaneous process, the entropy of the surroundings decreases - This option is incorrect because it is the entropy of the universe that necessarily increases. The universe consists of the system and surroundings which may or may not display increases in entropy respectively.

question.text: Which of the following molecules is the oxidizing agent in the reaction below? 2 H 2 O + SO 2 + I 2 H 2 SO 4 + 2 HI

explanation.concept_text: The oxidizing agent is a substance that has the ability to oxidize other substances; in other words, it gains electrons and is reduced in a chemical reaction. In contrast, a reducing agent is a substance that loses an electron to an electron recipient in a redox chemical reaction; in other words, it loses electrons and is oxidized in a chemical reaction. Going back to the question, we must begin by assigning oxidation numbers. Remember, hydrogen is +1 when bound to a non-metal, oxygen is usually -2 (unless in a peroxide), an element in elemental form (i.e. I 2 ) is 0, and any remaining oxidation numbers must calculated such that the total sum of the numbers equal the charge on the molecule: H 2 O  +  SO 2 + I 2 H 2 SO 4 + 2HI +1 -2   +4 -2     0       +1 +6 -2    +1 -1 In the above schematic, we can see that the oxidation numbers for Sulfur and Iodine undergo a change. Between SO 2 and H 2 SO 4 , the oxidation number on S increases from +4 to +6 which represents a loss of electrons (oxidation). Between I 2 and HI, the oxidation number is reduced from 0 to -1 which represents a gain of electrons (reduction). Since I 2 contains the atom that was reduced in the reaction, I 2 is the oxidizing agent.

question.text: The mass number remains unchanged in each of the following types of radioactive decay EXCEPT one. Which one is the EXCEPTION?

explanation.concept_text: Radioactive decay is a process that occurs in unstable atomic nuclei. There are many different types radioactive decay that may occur depending on the size of the nuclei and whether the instability is due to an abundance of protons or neutrons. The various types of radioactive decay are summarized in the table below. Out of the different types of radioactive decay processes, the nucleus emits an alpha particle or a helium nuclei only during an alpha decay . This results in a loss of two protons and two neutrons, causing the atomic number (number of protons) to decrease by 2, and the mass number (number of protons + neutrons) to decrease by 4. Therefore, the answer is Option A. Alpha decay since it leads to a change in mass number. CC BY 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option B. Electron capture - This option is incorrect because during electron capture, an electron converts a proton into a neutron. The atomic number decreases by 1, but the mass number remains unchanged as the lost proton is accounted for by the neutron. Option C. Positron emission - This option is incorrect because during positron emission, a positron is emitted as a proton is converted into a neutron. The atomic number decreases by 1, but the mass number remains unchanged as the lost proton is accounted for by the neutron. Option D. Beta-decay - This option is incorrect because during beta decay, an electron is emitted as a neutron is converted into a proton. The atomic number increases by 1, but the mass number remains unchanged as the lost neutron is accounted for by the proton. Option E. Gamma-decay - This option is incorrect because during gamma decay, a photon is emitted. The atomic number and the mass number remain unchanged.

Which of the following statements is true regarding electrochemical cells?

options.label: A.
options.text: The anode is the site of reduction

options.label: B.
options.text: Electrons flow from the cathode to the anode

options.label: D.
options.text: In galvanic cells, the cathode is positive and the anode is negative

options.label: E.
options.text: Anions flow to the cathode through the salt bridge

correct_answer_text: In galvanic cells, the cathode is positive and the anode is negative

explanation.concept_text: Electrochemical cells are systems that can generate electrical energy from a chemical reaction, or utilize electrical energy in order to cause a chemical reaction. One type of electrochemical cell is a galvanic cell, also called a voltaic cell, which is shown in the image below. Galvanic cells derive electrical energy from spontaneous redox (reduction and oxidation) reactions. This is in contrast to electrolytic cells , where instead, electrical energy is being used to drive a reaction. In both cells, electrons flow from the anode to cathode, where reduction always takes place at the cathode. The key difference between these cells is that in a galvanic cell, the anode is negative while the cathode is positive; the reverse is true in an electrolytic cell. CC BY 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option A. The anode is the site of reduction - This option is incorrect because the anode is the site of oxidation (“An Ox”) while the cathode is the site of reduction (“Red Cat”). Option B. Electrons flow from the cathode to the anode - This option is incorrect because electrons always flow from anode to cathode. Option C. Electrolytic cells are spontaneous - This option is incorrect because electrolytic cells are non-spontaneous, while galvanic (voltaic) cells are spontaneous. Option E. Anions flow to the cathode through the salt bridge - This option is incorrect because anions flow to the anode through the salt bridge, while cations flow to the cathode (CATions – CAThode).

question.text: Which of the following has the highest specific heat capacity?

explanation.concept_text: Specific heat is the amount of heat per unit mass required to raise the temperature by one degree Celsius. Specific heat depends on the strength of the intermolecular forces present. The higher the specific heat, the more energy is required to increase the temperature to the same extent as an element with lower specific heat. As a result, stronger intermolecular forces would be more resistant to a change in temperature and therefore have higher specific heat. The order of the strength of intermolecular forces is shown below: Ion-dipole forces > Hydrogen bonds > Dipole-dipole forces > London dispersion forces Going back to the question, the correct answer is Option E. CH 3 OH because it displays hydrogen bonding, which is the strongest compared to the other options, and therefore would be most resistant to change in temperature.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. CH 4 - This compound only displays London dispersion forces. Therefore, this option is incorrect . Option B. CCl 4 - This compound only displays London dispersion forces. Therefore, this option is incorrect . Option C. CO - This compound only displays London dispersion forces and dipole-dipole forces. Therefore, this option is incorrect . Option D. (CH 3 ) 4 Si - This compound only displays London dispersion forces. Therefore, this option is incorrect .

Which of the following compounds has the highest melting point?

explanation.concept_text: The melting point is the temperature at which a given solid will melt. It is primarily determined by the compound's intermolecular forces , which are the interactions that occur between molecules and neighboring particles. Stronger intermolecular forces mean increased interactions holding a substance together. Thus, stronger intermolecular forces result in a higher melting point, boiling point, viscosity, and surface tension, but a lower vapor pressure. The typical order of the strength of intermolecular forces is shown below: Ion-dipole forces > Hydrogen bonds > Dipole-dipole forces > London dispersion forces However, the molecular weight can also play an important role in determining the melting point. When the molecular weight of a molecule increases, the number of electrons within the molecule also increases. Having a larger electron cloud means that the molecule is more polarizable, and therefore there is an increase in the strength of London dispersion forces. Going back to the question, given that there is a large difference in molecular weights between the four compounds, the determining factor is the molecular weight rather than polarity. From the option choices, CBr 4 has the highest molecular weight (332 g/mol) compared to the other compounds, giving it relatively strong London Dispersion forces. Therefore, the answer is Option E. CBr 4 as it has the strongest intermolecular forces and thus, the highest melting point.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. CH 4 - This option is incorrect because the molecular weight is 16 g/mol, which is less than CBr 4 . Option B. CH 3 Br - This option is incorrect because the molecular weight is 95 g/mol, which is less than CBr 4 . Option C. CH 2 Br 2 - This option is incorrect because the molecular weight is 174 g/mol, which is less than CBr 4 . Option D. CHBr 3 - This option is incorrect because the molecular weight is 253 g/mol, which is less than CBr 4 .

question.text: Which of the following is diamagnetic?

explanation.concept_text: Diamagnetism results when an external magnetic field induces the electronic cloud to shift in such a way to generate an opposing magnetic field. This causes a weak repulsion of the material from the magnet. Since diamagnetism results from an induced magnetic field, all atoms or molecules with any paired electrons will exhibit diamagnetism. Paramagnetism results when an atom or molecule has any unpaired electrons. In this case, the unpaired electrons align themselves with an external magnetic field that generates an attractive force that greatly counteracts the weaker repulsion effect of diamagnetism. We recognize that hydrogen has a single electron in the 1s orbital. Atomic hydrogen would therefore be paramagnetic due to this unpaired electron. However, in anionic hydrogen, there is an extra electron resulting in a fully filled 1s orbital. Therefore, the correct answer is Option B.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. K – This option is incorrect because Potassium has an electron configuration of [Ar] 4s 1 with an unpaired electron in the 4s orbital, so it is paramagnetic. Option C. Li – This option is incorrect because lithium has an unpaired electron in the 2s orbital so it is paramagnetic. Option D. O 2 – This option is incorrect because O 2 is a diatomic element specially characterized by paramagnetism. Option E. Cu 2+ – This option is incorrect because copper has an electron configuration of [Ar] 3d 9 with an unpaired electron in the 3d orbital so it is paramagnetic.
